What is Alumina?
Alumina, chemically known as aluminum oxide (Al₂O₃), is a white, crystalline powder produced mainly from bauxite ore via the Bayer process. It functions as the principal feedstock for aluminum production, accounting for more than 90 % of global alumina consumption. The remaining volume serves specialized applications such as refractories, abrasives, high‑performance ceramics, catalysts, and activated alumina for water‑treatment and gas‑purification systems. High‑purity variants are increasingly sought after in advanced electronics, medical implants, and LED substrates because of their exceptional thermal stability, electrical insulation, and mechanical strength.
